Heat tolerance in ectotherms scales predictably
with body size
Ignacio Peralta-Maraver 
 1,2 and Enrico L. Rezende 
 3 ✉
Recent studies suggest that animals are decreasing in size as a general response to global warming, for reasons that remain
unclear. Here, by analysing ectotherm death time curves that take into consideration the intensity and duration of a thermal
challenge, we show that heat tolerance varies predictably with size. Smaller animals can maintain higher body temperatures
than larger ones during short periods, but cannot maintain higher body temperatures over long periods as their endurance
declines more rapidly with time. Body size effects and adaptive variation in heat tolerance may have been obscured in the past
by these unaccounted for temporal effects. With increasing size, thermal death occurs at relatively lower metabolic rates with
respect to rest at a non-stressful temperature, which might partly explain the reported reductions in organism size with climate
warming and shed light on the mechanisms that underlie scaling.
Recent studies have suggested that animals on average are
decreasing in size as a general response to increasing tem-
peratures1–4, although the mechanisms that explain such a
pattern remain poorly understood. Body size and ambient tem-
perature are widely recognized as major drivers of metabolic rate
variation across living organisms5,6, which explains why these
variables are often included in attempts to unify the study of eco-
logical patterns and processes under a single unified conceptual
framework6. Interestingly, living organisms exhibit an enormous
range of variation in size, spanning up to 21 orders of magnitude7.
Given that previous studies suggest a scaling exponent of between
two-thirds and three-quarters (metabolic rates increase propor-
tionally with body size raised to these exponents)5, this translates to
a variation of roughly 14 to 15 orders of magnitude in metabolism.
Nonetheless, the range of temperatures in which organisms operate
remains quite narrow: between 0 °C and 40 °C for the overwhelm-
ing majority of life on Earth8. Given the physical and thermody-
namic constraints imposed by size and temperature, it is actually
remarkable that living organisms are able to maintain some degree
of energy and temperature balance. With the size and temperature
ranges described above, for instance, one should expect a variation
in surface area to volume ratios under geometric similarity to span
14 orders of magnitude and—given the nearly exponential effect
of temperature on chemical reaction rates—a 16- to 81-fold varia-
tion in resting metabolism, assuming a two- to threefold increase
every 10 °C (that is, a temperature coefficient, Q10, between 2 and
3). These observations raise an important problem, namely, how
organisms of contrasting body sizes cope with thermal varia-
tion in general and extreme temperatures in particular. Although
most attempts to study size and temperature effects have focused
on how these variables interact to determine energy expenditure
as a common currency, few studies have analysed whether ther-
mal tolerance varies predictably with size9,10. This is particularly
intriguing considering that many macroecological studies (such as
those focusing on the temperature–size rule) assume implicitly or
explicitly that ambient temperature and body size distribution are
somehow related.
Here we attempt to fill this gap and address whether heat toler-
ance varies predictably with body size in ectotherms. In this con-
text, we focus on heat tolerance because this trait—as conveyed
by the thermal performance curve—is generally easier to estimate
and to explain from a mechanistic perspective than cold tolerance
(not only is the expected drop in performance more abrupt as tem-
perature increases, it is also more straightforwards to discriminate
mortality from dormancy responses in experimental trials at high
temperatures; but see ref. 10). The estimation and comparison of
upper critical limits are also not confounded by potentially contrast-
ing physiological responses to subzero temperatures, such as freez-
ing or prolonged diapause11. Furthermore, scaling effects on upper
thermal limits may have important implications for predictive pur-
poses as average temperatures and thermal extremes are expected
to increase with ongoing global warming, and previous studies sug-
gest that some extinction might be directly related to environmental
temperatures surpassing the tolerance limits of many organisms,
particularly at lower latitudes5.
Contrasting with most analyses of heat tolerance that implicitly
(and incorrectly) assume that critical temperatures remain constant
through time, here we employ thermal death time (TDT) curves to
disentangle how thermal tolerance varies as a function of both the
intensity and the duration of the heat stress12. TDT curves describe
how the critical temperature (Tcrit) varies with exposure time (t) and
can be described with the following relationship:

In this context, we predict that CTmax should generally decrease
and the linear slope z become shallow as body size increases (Fig. 1).
This is because larger animals can (1) avoid acute increases in body
temperature to stressful levels by behavioural means combined with
a higher thermal inertia, relaxing selection for a high CTmax, and (2)
deplete their resources during a thermal stress at lower rates than
smaller organisms due to their lower mass-specific metabolism12–14.
Consequently, they should be able to sustain continuous thermal
stress for longer periods.
Body size effects in heat tolerance
We put these predictions to a test with two separate datasets (hereaf-
ter Datasets 1 and 2) on heat tolerance estimates in mollusk, arthro-
pod, fish, amphibian and reptile species (Fig. 2). Dataset 1 includes
single estimates of Tcrit that were compiled in previous reviews on
critical thermal limits15–17, complemented with information on the
duration of each assay t from the original sources (n = 328 measure-
ments, Fig. 2a), whereas Dataset 2 includes parameters (CTmax and
z) that characterize individual TDT curves in a different and more
restricted sample (n = 62 curves, Fig. 2b), estimated with linear
regressions of Tcrit as a function of log10t (equation (1)) and published
elsewhere12. We also recorded the relative survival (50% versus
100% mortality) and developmental stage (for example, egg, larva,
adult) for each of the estimates and obtained a working phylogenetic
hypothesis based on taxonomic information. Although most of the
estimates were obtained in animals smaller than 1 g, together, these
datasets include well-distributed observations across nine orders of
magnitude up to 2.6 kg (Supplementary Table 1). This range cov-
ers the vast majority of animals on earth18. Given the differences
between datasets, we proceeded to test for body size effects in heat
tolerance, employing a model comparison approach16 as described
in detail in the Methods (datasets and scripts to replicate analyses
are available in DRYAD repository; https://doi.org/10.5061/dryad.
zkh189380).
As heat tolerance varies as a function of time and this effect
depends on species-specific TDT curves (equation (1)), the linear
models required to test for scaling need to explicitly incorporate this
component. Consequently, for Dataset 1, we tested whether the lin-

with the intercept, body mass, time of exposure and the interaction

residual variation after controlling for other confounding factors (see
Methods) and M is the body mass (as grams of wet weight). Given

how the TDT intercept and slope, respectively, vary as a function of
M as CTmax(M) = β0 + βΜ log10M and –z(M) = βt + βtΜ log10M (as the

Subsequently, CTmax(M) and z(M) were estimated as the projec-
tions of PC1(M) = β0 + βΜ log10M onto the original dimensions. For
clarity, the linear models described above include only the relevant
parameters to test for scaling effects on heat tolerance; however,
model comparisons also controlled for assay type (dynamic versus
static), relative mortality and developmental stage, and assumed dif-
ferent phylogenetic structures, namely, a star versus a hierarchical
phylogeny by setting Pagel’s lambda (λ) as 0 or 1, respectively (Table
1). This is a standard procedure to manipulate the expected amount
of phylogenetic signal in a dataset (see Methods).
We employed Akaike information criterion (AIC) to select the
models that best fit the data, and Akaike weights (wi) to quantify
the relative support of each model in comparison to all alternative
models (and therefore Σ wi = 1). Results were consistent across the
two datasets, with linear models that include M (equations (2) and
(3)) resulting in smaller AIC than other models and a very high sup-
port (wi ≥ 91%; Table 1). The models with the best fit had r2 = 0.714
and 0.589 for Datasets 1 and 2, respectively. Furthermore, λ = 0 in
both analyses, suggesting that the models’ residuals exhibit little
to no phylogenetic structure (in contrast with values of M, which
show conspicuous phylogenetic signal in both datasets, based on
the wi > 0.99 for diagnostic analyses in this trait assuming λ = 1).
This seems to reflect at least in part adaptive variation (see below).
Coefficients of the linear models give rise to elevated CTmax and
reduced z with increasing size (Table 2), which provides strong sup-
port to our original prediction (compare Fig. 1b with Fig. 2c,f).
To collapse all of the available information into a single
grand-average model with equations describing scaling effects for
CTmax and z, we averaged values of parameter β, which were esti-
mated for each dataset (Table 2). We employed unweighted averages
as both datasets include a comparable number of independent mea-
surements (n = 328 versus 309 for Datasets 1 and 2, respectively)
and therefore rely on similar amounts of information. Overall, anal-
yses indicate that small organisms are generally more tolerant to an

Ecological and metabolic implications
These analyses show that small and large ectothermic organisms
respond differently to a heat challenge. As a general rule, smaller
organisms seem to exhibit a higher tolerance to thermal extremes
than larger organisms, but their survival rates tend to drop rapidly
in time, which results in less pronounced differences in heat toler-
ance at broader temporal windows (Fig. 2). From a methodological
and analytical perspective, our results highlight that smaller organ-
isms are more sensitive to the duration of thermal assays than larger
ones (Figs. 1 and 2). This is particularly important because end-
point estimates of heat tolerance are being increasingly used to esti-
mate thermal safety limits and resilience to global warming8,17,19,20,
which neglect the confounding effects arising from variable tem-
poral scales (see ref. 12). Given that t is expressed on a logarithmic
scale, short measurements may grossly overestimate thermal safety
margins in smaller organisms, as the observation that most Tcrit
estimates fall above 40 °C at t ≤ 1 h and below this temperature at
t ≥ 1 day would indicate (Fig. 2a).
Certainly, this depends on the temporal window in which ther-
mal selection might take place. For instance, although the average
Tcrit for Dataset 1 corresponds to 44.4 ± 8.9 °C (mean ± s.d.), stan-
dardized Tcrit for a 1 h and 24 h exposure amount to 38.9 ± 4.8 °C
and 33.6 ± 5.0 °C, respectively (standardization was accomplished
obtaining predicted Tcrit for a given t with the best fit model in
Table 1 and adding the residuals to account for the unexplained
variance). Not only do we obtain the predicted decrease in mean
values, but the variance in standardized Tcrit decreases to roughly
30% of the variance of the raw values, suggesting that this proce-
dure enhances the signal-to-noise ratio (Supplementary Figs. 1–3).
Accordingly, standardization to 24 h to match the temporal win-
dow of daily temperature averages substantially improves the linear
regressions of Tcrit versus absolute latitude (from r2 = 0.013, 1-tailed
P = 0.96 to r2 = 0.105, P = 1.72 × 10−9) and maximum temperature
(from r2 = 0.008, P = 0.113 to r2 = 0.14, P = 4.93 × 10−12), uncovering

b,c, Tcrit standardized for a 24 h exposure decreases with absolute latitude (b) and increases with mean daily temperature of the warmest month (c).
d, Standardized estimates of warming tolerance are smaller towards the tropics and exhibit substantially less variation than raw estimates neglecting
temporal effects in thermal tolerance (for comparative purposes, open grey symbols in panels b–d show raw estimates without removing temporal effects,
effectively pooling measurements obtained in trials lasting from minutes up to days). Warming tolerance was estimated as the difference between Tcrit—
standardized for a 24 h exposure—and the mean temperature of the warmest month to obtain comparable timescales. Due to the reported scaling on TDT
curves, standardization of Tcrit takes into account both the duration of the original measurement and M (see Fig. 1b).
adaptive variation in heat tolerance that remains undetected with
conventional approaches (Fig. 3). This result is supported by model
comparison analyses and suggests that the inclusion of absolute lati-
tude and maximum temperature improve the best models for both
datasets (Supplementary Table 2).
The main point, however, is that both tolerance and stress
must be quantified in comparable timescales for improved predic-
tive power, and temporal effects vary with size. It remains largely
unknown, for instance, whether changes in mean temperatures due
to global warming will have a differential impact in small versus
large organisms, and the same is true for temperature variability and
the increase in frequency of extreme events. Recent analytical tools
can predict microclimates with unprecedented spatial and tempo-
ral resolution21, hence we need more accurate estimations of how
organisms tolerate stressful temperatures from minutes up to days
or even weeks22 (note that, for many aquatic organisms, behavioural
thermoregulation may not be an option even in longer timespans).
Importantly, attempts to extrapolate our results to natural condi-
tions must take into consideration the potential impact of thermal
inertia in larger organisms which tends to buffer short-term fluc-
tuations in ambient temperatures22.
Scaling effects on heat tolerance have other important repercus-
sions. As TDT curves describe, by definition, the thermal condi-
tions in which homoeostasis is disrupted and metabolic rate can no
longer be sustained in time and drops to 0, our analyses imply that
larger organisms collapse at relatively lower metabolic levels with
respect to the standard metabolic rate at a non-stressful temperature
than smaller ones. In other words, thermal death occurs at relatively
lower metabolic rates as body size increases (Fig. 1). This can be
readily demonstrated analytically by combining our results with
the general relationship describing how metabolic rate is affected
by body size and temperature6 (see the Supplementary Information
for more details). With this procedure we obtain metabolic limits
that scale between three-quarters and two-thirds depending on the
amount of time that the metabolic rate can be sustained, which is
based on estimations of survival times (Fig. 1). These results are
consistent with the metabolic-level boundaries hypothesis23 and
indicate that the amount of time that a given metabolic rate can
be sustained constitutes a latent variable that might affect to some
degree most, if not all, studies on metabolic scaling. In principle,
this could be tested by determining if exposure time is a significant
predictor of metabolic rates under stressful temperature conditions.
To summarize, here we show that heat tolerance varies predict-
ably with body size. To our knowledge this is the first detailed anal-
ysis quantifying how thermal tolerance scales across organisms of
different body sizes, which include equations to estimate tolerated
temperatures that take into account the often-neglected impact of
exposure times to a thermal stress. This finding has profound impli-
62
NatuRE CLIMatE CHaNgE | VOL 11 | JAnUARy 2021 | 58–63 | www.nature.com/natureclimatechange

Page 6
cations to metabolic scaling studies and to understand how differ-
ent organism might respond to ongoing global warming. Recent
studies have suggested that shrinking sizes, which have been widely
reported for extinct and extant terrestrial and aquatic ectotherms
under warming conditions, may constitute a general response to
anthropogenic climate change1,2. This reduction in body size is cur-
rently proposed as a third universal response to global warming,
together with the displacement in species ranges and seasonal shifts
in life-cycle events3,4. Our results indicate that differences in heat
tolerance might be contributing to this pattern per se. In addition,
other factors that also scale with body size, such as abundance or
food and water requirements, may act in synergy increasing the
vulnerability of larger organisms to rapidly changing environmen-
tal conditions6,24. Importantly, although analyses involve different
species with contrasting body sizes, some empirical studies have
reported enhanced mortality of large individuals following warm-
ing conditions25, suggesting that the reported pattern might also
hold within species with potentially important consequences for
population dynamics. Nonetheless, broad generalizations should be
performed with caution because other factors, such as developmen-
tal stage and respiration strategy, correlate with size and can also
affect thermal performance9,10,25.

Methods
Data collection. Two different datasets were built and analysed in this study.
Dataset 1 comprises 328 empirical measurements of knockdown temperature (Tcrit)
and t for mollusk, arthropod, fish, amphibian and reptile species under different
experimental protocols, obtained from previous reviews in the literature15–17.
Reported Tcrit and t were quantified with two different experimental assays, in
which temperature remained constant throughout the assay (the so-called static
method) or was raised under controlled conditions at a known ramping rate
(dynamic method). As only Tcrit was generally reported for dynamic assays, we
compiled the starting experimental temperatures and ramping rates reported in
the original sources and calculated t from this information as t = (Tcrit – Tinitial)/
ramping rate. By contrast, Dataset 2 comprises 62 TDT curves, which involve
static assays at different temperatures to obtain a general relation between Tcrit
and t (equation (1)) for annelids, mollusks, arthropods and fish species compiled
from a previous study12. Each TDT curve represents a linear fit that involves
5.0 ± 1.6 (mean ± s.d.) different temperatures, adding to a total of 309 separate
measurements. We obtained estimates of M (as grams of wet weight) from multiple
sources (Supplementary Table 1 and DRYAD repository; https://doi.org/10.5061/
dryad.zkh189380)), and information on the relative percentage of survival (50%
versus 100% mortality) and the developmental stage (for example egg, larva, adult
and so on) for which thermal tolerance measurements were taken. More than one
Tcrit estimate was available for the 51 species in Dataset 1, and more than one TDT
curve for five species in Dataset 2 (Supplementary Fig. 4); however, we included
all values as separate measurements as they were obtained from different research
groups under different protocols and often at different life stages, and controlled for
possible non-independence of replicated measurements in a single species in the
phylogenetic analyses (see below).
We then obtained the collection site and estimates of M for all organisms
whose thermal tolerance was available in Datasets 1 and 2. Measurements of
M were collected from multiple sources (Supplementary Table 1 and DRYAD
repository; https://doi.org/10.5061/dryad.zkh189380). We employed the collection
sites to obtain maximum mean monthly air26 and sea-surface temperatures27 for
terrestrial and marine organisms, respectively, from 0.5° × 0.5° NOAA temperature
grids (https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/data/gridded/) and worked with the daily
averages of the warmest month for the calculation of thermal safety margins; M
was obtained from the original study or—when it was not accessible or reported—
after thoroughly searching 139 scientific articles and 6 online databases (see
DRYAD repository; https://doi.org/10.5061/dryad.zkh189380). Values that were
originally reported as dry weight or ash-free dry weight for some arthropods were
converted into wet weight, applying a proportion of wet weight to dry weight of
5:1, and a proportion of dry weight to ash-free dry weight of 10:9 (ref. 28). For those
cases in which M was not directly available, body dimensions (that is length and
width) were converted into wet weight using published body length taxa-specific
equations (Supplementary Table 1). In the case of eggs, dimensions were
transformed into wet weight using biovolumes regressions29. Finally, for the few
cases in which neither M or size were available, M was inferred from closely related
species within the same genera with similar sizes (33 species in Dataset 1 and 4
species in Dataset 2). The body size and exposure time ranged between 2.4 μg to
2.6 kg and 1 min to 16 days for Dataset 1, and between 3.7 μg to 210 g and 0.5 min to
56.5 days for Dataset 2 (see Supplementary Fig. 5 for additional details). Analysed
datasets including detailed information on the data sources are available via the
DRYAD repository (https://doi.org/10.5061/dryad.zkh189380).
Statistical analysis. To estimate scaling effects on the parameters of the TDT
curves, we combined multiple regression techniques with a model selection
approach30. Analyses were performed separately for Datasets 1 and 2 as described
in the main text. For Dataset 1, a single end-point Tcrit reported from a static
or dynamic assay was included as the response variable and log10-transformed
M and t as independent variables (equation (2)), also adding four categorical
factors to control differences in mortality (50% versus 100% reported mortality),
experimental assay (static versus dynamic), developmental stage and the original
literature review employed as the data source. This is because one of the reviews15
provided guidelines to remove pests from museum collections, resulting in higher
estimates on average than those from the other reviews since its main goal was
to ensure that pests were eradicated and not to measure tolerance per se. Other
methodological aspects known to affect Tcrit, such as acclimation temperature or the
number of generations in the laboratory, were not available in most of the original
studies and could not be included in our analyses.
To perform a comparable analysis with Dataset 2, we collapsed highly
correlated parameters CTmax and z into a single response variable (which accounted
for 98% of the original variance that employs a principal component analysis)
and included log10-transformed M as the independent variable (equation (3)),
also controlling for mortality and the developmental stage. In these regression
models, CTmax and z were mapped back to their original space afterwards by
multiplying PC1 by the transposed eigenvectors used for projection and rescaling
with the mean value of raw CTmax and z from TDT data (inverse to the centring
of the mean). Note that in this analysis we did not include t as an independent
variable as parameters CTmax and z embedded in the response variable describe
a function-valued trait that already incorporates temporal effects (equation (1)),
and experimental assay as an additional factor as all TDT curves are obtained with
static methods. With this procedure we were able to obtain general scaling relations
for parameters CTmax and z from datasets that are inherently different but convey
the same type of information.
To estimate and potentially control for the phylogenetic structure of regression
residuals, we employed taxonomic information to build coarse phylogenies for
both datasets. This is particularly suitable here because Datasets 1 and 2 encompass
very diverse taxa, hence set of nested taxonomic variables can be employed to
build relatively well-resolved and reliable phylogenies. Accordingly, by employing
variables that code for protostomes versus deuterostomes, phylum, class, order,
family and genus, we obtained phylogenies with 134 and 34 resolved nodes for
Datasets 1 and 2, respectively, and with Grafen’s arbitrary branch lengths we
retrieved very high phylogenetic signal for M in both datasets as a positive control
(λ = 1, wi > 0.99 in both cases). This was accomplished comparing phylogenetic
generalized least-squares regressions, assuming a hierarchical structure conveyed
by the phylogeny (λ = 1) against a star structure indicating phylogenetic
independence (λ = 0).
Finally, we employed AIC to find the best candidate for the inferential lineal
models and phylogenetic structure30,31. Models containing only correcting factors
were fitted first. Predictors and first-order interactions were then included
sequentially, and the model was refitted at each time; wi were employed to
estimate the weight of evidence in favour of each candidate model, which gives the
probability of the candidate model being the correct one compared with the other
models tested. Regression results for the models with the best fit are available in
Supplementary Tables 3 and 4.
